{{Otheruses|Perimeter fences around shrines}} {{Multiple issues|Uncited=August 28, 2017|Original research=August 28, 2017}} [[File:Owari_Oomiwa_Shrine_honden.jpeg|thumb|right|267x267px|Tamagaki surrounding the main shrine hall]] [[File:Tachibanajinjya_06c0859x.jpg|thumb|right|200x200px|Tamagaki surrounding the precincts]] '''Tamagaki''' (玉垣) refers to fences constructed around {{ill|Shinto shrines|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} or sacred areas ({{ill|shin'iki|ja|神域|12=draft|12=draft}}). It is also known as '''Mizugaki''' (瑞垣).
== Overview ==
=== Origins and Evolution === As {{ill|Shinto shrine practices|ja|神社神道|12=draft|12=draft}} became formalized and structures such as {{ill|shrine halls|ja|社|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|haiden|ja|拝殿|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|honden|ja|本殿|12=draft|12=draft}} were established, the boundaries of shrine precincts became clearly demarcated. This distinction between the ambiguous boundary of the spiritual ({{ill|Tokoyo|ja|常世|12=draft|12=draft}}) and the physical world ({{ill|Utsushiyo|ja|現世|12=draft|12=draft}}) evolved, transitioning from simple arrangements of sacred trees ({{ill|himorogi|ja|神籬|1=Himorogi|12=draft|12=draft}}) and rocks ({{ill|iwa|ja|磐座|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|iwazakai|ja|磐境|12=draft|12=draft}}) to more formal stone or wooden fences that define modern shrine layouts.
=== Types and Styles === The oldest form of tamagaki is thought to be {{ill|shibagaki|ja|柴垣|12=draft|12=draft}}, fences made from entwined tree branches. Various styles have emerged, including: * '''Ita-tamagaki''': Fences made from thick wooden planks. * '''Kuroki-tamagaki''': Made from wood with the bark still attached. * '''Sukigaki''': Fences with widely spaced slats.
Materials vary from wood and stone to modern concrete. Tamagaki often bear inscriptions of the names of those who contributed them as offerings.
== Terminology == ; Synonyms Tamagaki has synonymous terms, including '''Mizugaki''' (瑞垣), '''Imigaki''' (斎垣), and '''Kamigaki''' (神垣), all meaning the same: a sacred fence. The inside of the fence is called "Kakitzu" (垣内), and the outside is "Kaito" (垣外). The terms "tama," "mizu," and "imi" signify sacred or beautiful, combining with "gaki" (fence) to mean "a beautiful sacred enclosure for the gods."
; Differentiation in multi-layered fences Shrines may have multiple layers of tamagaki, distinguished by specific names. The innermost fence is often called Mizugaki, while the outer layers are termed differently depending on the shrine, such as '''Itagaki''' (板垣) for the outermost fence or '''Aragaki''' (荒垣). For instance, at {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, there are four concentric fences named, from innermost to outermost, Mizugaki, Uchitamagaki (内玉垣), Sototamagaki (外玉垣), and Itagaki.
== Ritual Equipment == As ritual equipment, miniature tamagaki are used to decorate {{ill|kamidana|ja|神棚|12=draft|12=draft}}, mimicking the fences seen at shrines.
== Notes == == See Also == * {{ill|Kannabi|ja|神奈備|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Himorogi|ja|神籬|1=Himorogi|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Iwakura|ja|磐座|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Chinju-no-mori|ja|鎮守の森|12=draft|12=draft}}
